<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-615-215  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 615 215.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Nov 12 1990 n616 p121(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>'Mommy track' derails some engineers; flex time, pregnancy leavesnot always available. (motherhood and an engineering career)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ryan, Margaret.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many women engineers who expected to find opportunities inelectronics industries are finding instead that employers are notoften cooperative when it comes to motherhood and an engineeringcareer.andP;  Many electronics and computer companies do not offerdependent-care programs, extended maternity and parental leave andpart-time, flex-time and job-share schedules, although suchprograms are becoming increasingly available.andP;  A Conference Boardsurvey released in the summer of 1990 found that 93 percent of the521 corporations surveyed offer some type of flexible schedule forcore employees; more firms are offering alternative work schedulesas male and female parents continue to demand them and the pool ofskilled labor continues to shrink.andP;  Overtime-intensiveprofessions, such as engineering and law, are much slower to adoptflexible work schedules, according to industry analysts.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Social IssuesWomenEngineeringEmployee BenefitsFlextimeScheduling.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>